Boil a #large pot{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Peel and very finely chop the @garlic{2%cloves}. Peel the @onion{1/2}(peeled and sliced into thin half moon shapes). Chop the @black olives{2} up into tiny bits. Pull the @oregano{1/2} leaves from their stalks and finely chop the leaves.

Add @olive oil{1%tbsp} to a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once warm, add the garlic and onion and cook gently for around ~{5%minutes}. You want to cook the onion until it is soft, but don't let it colour too much.

> You can add 1 tbsp of water and turn the heat down if it's cooking too quickly.

Add the @chopped tomatoes{1}, @tomato puree{1%tomato puree} (in original text likely a small can or equivalent), chopped olives and oregano to your pan. Stir in @salt{1/4%tsp} and @?sugar{1/4%tsp} (if you have some). Allow to bubble gently on medium-low heat for around ~{10%minutes}.

Cook the @rigatoni pasta{200%g} in the boiling water for around ~{11%minutes} or until 'al dente'.

> 'Al dente' simply means that the pasta is cooked through but has a slight hint of firmness left in the middle. Test for 'doneness' as you go until it is just right.

When you drain your pasta with a #colander{} save a few tbsp of the pasta water before you do so.

> Italians often use a bit of pasta water to loosen up the tomato sauce a little - stir a bit through your sauce if needs be.

Roughly chop the @basil{1/2%bunch}(roughly chopped, keeping a little back for garnish) and stir them through your pasta sauce, together with your drained pasta, then toss all your ingredients together.

Serve with a scattering of chopped basil leaves and tear over chunks of the @mozzarella{1}. Add a pinch of @freshly ground black pepper{} and get stuck in.